question:
Consider the real sequence \(\langle a_n \rangle = \left\langle \tfrac12, \tfrac14, \tfrac34, \tfrac18, \tfrac78, \tfrac1{16}, \tfrac{15}{16}, \dots \right\rangle\), defined by
\[
a_n =
\begin{cases}
\dfrac{1}{2^{(n+2)/2}} & \text{if } n \text{ is even},\\[6pt]
1 - \dfrac{1}{2^{(n+1)/2}} & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
\end{cases}
\]Let \(R = \{a_n : n \in \mathbb{N}\}\) be the range of the sequence. Consider the statements:
I. The limit \(\displaystyle\lim_{n \to \infty} a_n\) does not exist.
II. There exist subsequences of \(\langle a_n \rangle\) converging to \(0\) and to \(1\), respectively.
III. Both \(0\) and \(1\) are accumulation points of the set \(R\).
Which of the above statements are true?
options: D: I and II are true, but III is false.
E: I, II, and III are all true.

Question:
Consider the real sequence \(\langle a_n \rangle = \left\langle \tfrac12, \tfrac14, \tfrac34, \tfrac18, \tfrac78, \tfrac1{16}, \tfrac{15}{16}, \dots \right\rangle\), defined by
\[
a_n =
\begin{cases}
\dfrac{1}{2^{(n+2)/2}} & \text{if } n \text{ is even},\\[6pt]
1 - \dfrac{1}{2^{(n+1)/2}} & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
\end{cases}
\]Let \(R = \{a_n : n \in \mathbb{N}\}\) be the range of the sequence. Consider the statements:
I. The limit \(\displaystyle\lim_{n \to \infty} a_n\) does not exist.
II. There exist subsequences of \(\langle a_n \rangle\) converging to \(0\) and to \(1\), respectively.
III. Both \(0\) and \(1\) are accumulation points of the set \(R\).
Which of the above statements are true?

Options:
A: Only I is true.
B: Only II is true.
C: Only III is true.
D: I and II are true, but III is false.
E: I, II, and III are all true.

message.content:
Even terms: \(a_{2k} = \dfrac{1}{2^{k+1}}\to 0\).

Odd terms: \(a_{2k-1} = 1 - \dfrac{1}{2^{k}}\to 1\).

So \(\langle a_n\rangle\) has two subsequences with different limits, hence the overall limit does not exist ⇒ I true.  

The subsequence \(\{a_{2k}\}\) converges to \(0\) and \(\{a_{2k-1}\}\) converges to \(1\) ⇒ II true.  

Since there are infinitely many terms of the sequence arbitrarily close to \(0\) and to \(1\), both 0 and 1 are accumulation points of the range \(R\) ⇒ III true.

Answer:E

question:
Let \(A=(0,1)\) and
\[
\mathcal{G}=\{G_n:(0,1)\to\mathbb{R}\mid G_n=(\tfrac{1}{n+2},\tfrac{1}{n}),\,n\in\mathbb{N}\}.
\]
Then \(\mathcal{G}\) is an open cover of \(A\). 
Which of the following statements correctly describes why the union of no finite subcollection of \(\mathcal{G}\) equals \(A\)?
options: A: In any finite subcollection \(\{G_{n_1},\dots,G_{n_k}\}\), the minimum of the left endpoints  \(a=\min_i \tfrac{1}{n_i+2}\) is positive, so all points in \((0,a)\subset A\) remain uncovered.
B: In any finite subcollection, the largest right endpoint is less than \(1\), so the point \(0\) is not covered.
C: Any finite union of open intervals in \(\mathbb{R}\) is closed, so it cannot equal the open set \(A\).
D: Because \(\mathcal{G}\) is countable, no finite subcollection can cover the uncountable set \(A\).
E: Each interval \(G_n\) contains the point \(0\), so no finite union of them can cover points near \(1\).

Question:
Let \(A=(0,1)\) and
\[
\mathcal{G}=\{G_n:(0,1)\to\mathbb{R}\mid G_n=(\tfrac{1}{n+2},\tfrac{1}{n}),\,n\in\mathbb{N}\}.
\]
Then \(\mathcal{G}\) is an open cover of \(A\). 
Which of the following statements correctly describes why the union of no finite subcollection of \(\mathcal{G}\) equals \(A\)?

Options:
A: In any finite subcollection \(\{G_{n_1},\dots,G_{n_k}\}\), the minimum of the left endpoints  \(a=\min_i \tfrac{1}{n_i+2}\) is positive, so all points in \((0,a)\subset A\) remain uncovered.
B: In any finite subcollection, the largest right endpoint is less than \(1\), so the point \(0\) is not covered.
C: Any finite union of open intervals in \(\mathbb{R}\) is closed, so it cannot equal the open set \(A\).
D: Because \(\mathcal{G}\) is countable, no finite subcollection can cover the uncountable set \(A\).
E: Each interval \(G_n\) contains the point \(0\), so no finite union of them can cover points near \(1\).

message.content:
A is correct: For any finite subcollection, say indices \(n_1,\dots,n_k\), the union is  
\(\bigcup_{i=1}^k (\tfrac{1}{n_i+2},\tfrac{1}{n_i}) = (a,b)\cup\cdots\), where the smallest left endpoint is \(a=\min_i \tfrac{1}{n_i+2}>0\). Then every point in \((0,a)\subset (0,1)\) is not covered, so the union cannot be all of \(A\).

B is wrong: even the whole union has all right endpoints \(<1\), but that only shows it does not cover points near \(1\), while the crucial obstruction in a finite subcover is near \(0\), not \(1\). Also, 0 is not in \(A\).

C is wrong: a finite union of open intervals in \(\mathbb{R}\) is open, not necessarily closed.

D is wrong: countability vs uncountability is irrelevant; a countable open cover can have a finite subcover in many cases.

E is wrong: no \(G_n\) contains 0, and they do cover points near 1 (e.g. \(G_1=(1/3,1)\)).

Answer:A
